## 21. Why This Design Was Chosen

This prototype was built to satisfy hackathon-style goals:

- simple local setup
- easy demo flow
- visible approval engine
- role-based behavior
- clear navigation
- enough backend logic to prove the idea

Using SQLite for the prototype reduces friction and keeps the app runnable without external database setup.

Keeping rules in the database instead of hardcoding them makes the project stronger conceptually and closer to a real enterprise workflow system.

## 22. Current Prototype Limits

Important limitations in the current version:

- real-time notifications are not implemented yet
- fraud detection is not implemented yet
- OCR is best-effort only
- exchange conversion fallback is basic if no API key is provided
- override approvals are not yet a dedicated admin action
- SQLite is used for prototype simplicity instead of PostgreSQL

## 23. What Would Be Next for Production

If this were extended beyond prototype stage, the next upgrades should be:

- restore PostgreSQL as primary database
- use proper Prisma migrations end-to-end
- add Socket.io for real-time notifications
- add stronger file storage strategy
- add duplicate receipt detection
- add admin override workflow
- add better manager tree handling beyond direct reports
- add better analytics and export
- add test coverage for approval rules

## 24. Final Summary

This app is a reimbursement workflow platform.

Employees submit expenses.
Managers and admins review them.
Rules stored in the database decide how approvals work.
All expenses are normalized into the company currency.
The frontend gives a clean soft-themed interface.
The backend enforces auth, roles, approval logic, and data separation.

For the current prototype, everything runs locally using React, Express, Prisma client, and a SQLite database file.
